                          "String": "SURFACE WATER: Chlorobenzene was detected in water collected near an industrial outfall in Bayou d'Inde, LA at a concn of 18 ng/L(1). Water samples collected from various locations in and around the Ho-Chin River of Taiwan were found to contain chlorobenzene ranging in concentrations from 1.6 to 1.65 ug/L(2). Chlorobenzene was identified in an analysis of subsurface riverine and marine waters conducted at the mouths of the Besos and Llobregat Rivers near Barcelona, Spain(3). The concentration of chlorobenzene in the Besos and Llobregat Rivers near Barcelona, Spain was determined to be 260 and 210 ng/L, respectively; chlorobenzene was not identified in adjacent marine coastal waters(4). Chlorobenzene was identified in an aqueous sample collected near Quantico, VA as having a concentration of <2 ug/L(5). Chlorobenzene was identified in surface water/groundwater samples impacted by municipal landfill leachate in Orange County, Alachua County (southwest), and Alachua County (southeast), FL as having concentrations ranging from <0.20 to 302 ug/L(6). The analysis of 315 water samples collected between February and June 1987 from the municipal water supply of Santiago De Compostela, Spain showed no chlorobenzene present(7). The level of chlorobenzene detected in urban rivers and their estuaries in Osaka, Japan was approximately 0.21 ug/L(8). Annual flux of chlorobenzene concentrations in four industrialized rivers (Aire, Calder, Don and Trent) of the Southern Humber Cachment UK were 2.52, 0.94, 0.12 and 3.84 kg/yr, respectively; rivers monitored weekly from February 1995 to February 1997(9).",
