                          "String": "Chlorobenzene has been detected in municipal landfill leachate at concentrations ranging from 1 to 685 g/L(1). Chlorobenzene was identified as one of the most frequently observed anthropogenic-specific compounds in landfill leachates; concentrations range from 0.1 to 110 ug/L(2). The concentration of chlorobenzene detected in gas samples from wells in 3 old and 1 active municipal landfills in southern Finland ranged from <0.01 to 0.19 mg/cu m(3). Chlorobenzene was detected at 6 sites in Ontario, Canada in shallow aquifers that had been impacted by landfill leachate, concentrations ranging from <0.2 to 10 ug/L(4). Chlorobenzene was detected but not quantified in emissions from municipal wastewater treatment plants located throughout California(5). Chlorobenzene was identified in raw wastewater of Love Canal, NY landfill leachate as having an approximate concentration of 12.2 mg/L(6). The emission of chlorobenzene from the combustion of pulverized coal has been calculated to range from 1.30X10-7 lb/10+6 Btu for baseline coal to 1.95X10-7 lb/10+6 BTU under low NOx conditions(7). Chlorobenzene was detected at concentrations ranging from 0.0051 to 0.536 g/hr in emissions from 4 municipal wastewater sludge incinerators located throughout California(8).",
